01:39.080 --> 01:41.231
Well, Chester, I just can't believe it.

01:41.440 --> 01:45.719
I mean, Chester,
to think that one of our own relatives
might be a murderer.

01:45.920 --> 01:46.920
A murderer.

01:47.080 --> 01:51.757
I mean, I spent the whole evening
with a murderer,
I fed dinner to a murderer.

01:52.280 --> 01:56.513
Actually, I might be living in
the same house with a murderer.

01:56.720 --> 01:59.474
Chester, who do you think did it?

01:59.680 --> 02:02.320
Who could have done it?
Who cares, Jessica?

02:03.840 --> 02:07.311
After what I learned this evening,
I couldn't care less about a murder.

02:07.520 --> 02:09.670
Oh, what did you learn?

02:13.440 --> 02:15.671
Oh, that. Heh.

02:15.880 --> 02:17.678
Yes, that.
Uh-huh.

02:17.880 --> 02:21.954
Uh, Chester, do you think that we
are talking about the same "that"?

02:22.160 --> 02:24.550
I think so.
Uh-huh.

02:24.760 --> 02:26.319
You're talking about that "that",

02:26.520 --> 02:29.319
that has something to do
with me and, uh, someone else?

02:29.520 --> 02:31.796
That's right.
Oh, that. Oh.

02:32.000 --> 02:36.119
Yeah, well, that is the "that" that
I thought that you were talking about.

02:36.680 --> 02:39.798
Well, Chester, I...
I don't see what the big deal is.

02:40.000 --> 02:44.074
I mean, I told you I had had an affair.
I mean, you did know about it.

02:44.280 --> 02:46.511
But I didn't know who, Jessica.

02:46.720 --> 02:49.713
I didn't know who you
were having your affair with.

02:49.920 --> 02:52.879
Well, I... I should think
it would come as a relief.

02:53.080 --> 02:54.150
Relief?
Yes.

02:54.360 --> 02:55.919
Doesn't it make you feel better
to know

02:56.120 --> 02:59.079
that I had an affair
with someone who's dead?

02:59.560 --> 03:01.631
I... I mean, someone who's dead now.

03:01.840 --> 03:04.230
I mean, it should make it
much easier, Chester.

03:04.440 --> 03:06.477
You'll never bump into each other
at a party.

03:06.680 --> 03:10.435
And you'll never have to look at him
and picture, uh...

03:18.920 --> 03:22.311
I assumed, Jessica, when you told me
you were having an affair

03:22.520 --> 03:27.959
that at least, at the very least,
you were having a dignified one.

03:29.920 --> 03:32.879
But to discover
that you were robbing the cradle...

03:33.080 --> 03:34.594
Do you know how that looks?

03:34.800 --> 03:37.190
Do you know
what people say about that?

03:37.400 --> 03:41.440
Well, when men do it
they say "congratulations."

03:41.640 --> 03:44.474
That's something else entirely,
Jessica.

03:44.680 --> 03:49.197
Young girls
are attracted to older men.
It's a known fact.

03:49.400 --> 03:51.278
We can't help it.

03:52.360 --> 03:56.036
Yes, you can. You could say no.

03:56.240 --> 04:00.120
He was a boy. An absolute boy.
Ha-ha.

04:00.320 --> 04:03.757
It must have been wonderful.
I'm sure you had a lot to talk about.
Ha-ha.

04:03.960 --> 04:06.077
No, we didn't. Heh.

04:08.640 --> 04:10.154
Well, I wouldn't think so.

04:10.360 --> 04:12.511
A... Actually, there was never
very much time.

04:12.720 --> 04:14.720
I mean, you know,
it is kind of hard to talk and...

04:14.800 --> 04:16.870
Uh... Spare me.

04:17.079 --> 04:19.276
At the same time.

04:19.959 --> 04:21.553
Well, Chester, I'm sorry.

04:21.760 --> 04:24.434
Well, must have been exciting, huh?
Heh.

04:24.640 --> 04:27.951
Of course,
a young, good-looking guy.

04:28.160 --> 04:32.552
Probably knows all kinds
of tricks they're doing these days.

04:33.240 --> 04:35.357
They've got all these new books.

04:35.560 --> 04:38.439
Well, Chester, it didn't last long.

04:38.640 --> 04:40.757
When I was growing up,
we didn't have books.

04:40.960 --> 04:43.794
There was one way to do it.

04:44.000 --> 04:46.037
Chester, are you jealous?

04:46.240 --> 04:50.359
I mean, the guy has got energy. Heh.
And tricks.

04:50.560 --> 04:52.438
How can you compete?

04:52.640 --> 04:55.235
He grew up on <i>Penthouse.</i>

04:55.440 --> 04:58.751
I grew up on <i>National Geographic.</i>

04:59.720 --> 05:02.519
Why should I know
as much as he does?

05:02.720 --> 05:05.440
Chester, I'm here.

05:05.640 --> 05:07.279
Look at me.

05:07.480 --> 05:09.472
I'm here.
Of course you're here.

05:09.680 --> 05:10.830
He's dead.

05:13.440 --> 05:16.717
Well, I was still here
when he was alive.

05:16.920 --> 05:20.277
Now you know how I felt
all those years, Chester.

05:20.480 --> 05:21.960
You felt this way?

05:22.160 --> 05:25.153
Mm. Every time.

05:26.160 --> 05:29.039
And it was an awful lot
of times, Chester.

05:29.240 --> 05:30.799
Feels awful.

05:31.000 --> 05:32.514
I know.

05:32.720 --> 05:37.431
Sometimes I felt so awful,
I thought I was going to throw up.

05:38.920 --> 05:44.200
Except, of course, I hate to throw up.
I haven't thrown up since 1948.

05:46.040 --> 05:48.316
I don't think I've ever
felt like this before.

05:48.520 --> 05:50.034
I know.

05:50.240 --> 05:52.197
[♪♪♪]

05:52.560 --> 05:54.916
I'm sorry, Jess.

05:56.040 --> 05:58.760
I'm sorry you ever had
to feel this way.

05:59.520 --> 06:01.477
I'm really sorry.

06:01.960 --> 06:06.034
Chester, let's try

06:06.240 --> 06:09.631
never to make each other
feel this way again. Hmm?

06:20.240 --> 06:21.993
Thank you.

06:23.120 --> 06:25.760
Boy, it sure is quiet around here.

06:25.960 --> 06:29.112
Hey, guys, what's the matter?
Did somebody die? Ha-ha-ha.

06:30.520 --> 06:32.910
[ALL TALKING INDISTINCTLY]

06:33.120 --> 06:34.120
Take it easy, Burt.

06:34.320 --> 06:36.994
Come on. Don't you have any
feelings? He was your brother.

06:37.200 --> 06:39.351
It wasn't my brother, you idiot.
It was his.

06:39.560 --> 06:42.473
Don't call my father an idiot.

06:42.840 --> 06:44.559
Excuse me.

06:45.160 --> 06:47.391
I'm sorry, Dad.
It's all right.

06:47.600 --> 06:49.193
It's all right. It's all right.
No, I'm all right.

06:49.400 --> 06:52.040
I'm all right, I'm all right.
I'm all right.

06:52.240 --> 06:54.800
Boy, you never know what life
has in store for you, huh?

06:55.000 --> 06:56.480
I mean, you just never know.

06:56.680 --> 06:59.149
Only a few days ago,
I'm the happiest guy in the world.

06:59.360 --> 07:02.080
And now today, I couldn't be sadder.

07:02.280 --> 07:04.033
I know, dear.
I don't know.

07:04.216 --> 07:05.976
I don't know. Maybe God looked down
and said:

07:06.000 --> 07:09.152
"Hey, uh, Campbell's too happy.
Let's cool him down. Kill his son."

07:09.360 --> 07:11.431
I don't know, I don't know.

07:11.640 --> 07:12.790
Well, I don't know.

07:13.000 --> 07:15.151
I mean, I don't know
what the world has come to.

07:15.360 --> 07:16.999
When someone in one's own family,

07:17.200 --> 07:19.669
is murdered by someone else
in someone's own family.

07:19.880 --> 07:22.839
Jessica, please, enough of this.
Nobody...

07:23.040 --> 07:25.874
Nobody killed anybody.
Oh, yeah?

07:26.080 --> 07:29.756
Well, somebody better tell Peter.
They buried him the other day.

07:30.600 --> 07:33.877
Peter was stabbed, shot, strangled,
suffocated and bludgeoned.

07:34.080 --> 07:36.595
Do you seriously think
that one of us could've done it? Heh.

07:36.800 --> 07:40.680
For God's sake, nobody in this family
could sit through <i>The Exorcist.</i>
Heh-heh.

07:40.880 --> 07:42.280
That's right.

07:42.480 --> 07:45.598
I just wonder if any of the Campbells
could sit through it.

07:45.800 --> 07:49.760
You know, I think I remember
one of them telling me
they loved that.

07:49.960 --> 07:52.316
Now which one was it?

07:52.520 --> 07:54.591
I just wonder which one
of the Tates did it.

07:54.800 --> 07:58.476
Burt, I find it very difficult to believe
that one of the Tates is a murderer.

07:58.680 --> 08:00.831
Oh, you do, do you, huh?
Well... Well, I don't.

08:01.040 --> 08:02.997
It was one of them. I know it.

08:03.200 --> 08:04.395
Probably Jessica.

08:04.600 --> 08:06.034
She couldn't have, Burt.

08:06.240 --> 08:07.640
Not in a million years.

08:07.840 --> 08:09.320
Mary, please,
do you ever talk to that woman?

08:09.520 --> 08:12.240
She's got a vacuum cleaner bag
up here.

08:12.440 --> 08:15.399
You know, Jessica told me
she talks to flowers.

08:15.600 --> 08:18.320
Lots of people do that.
I talk to my fern.

08:18.520 --> 08:20.512
Yeah, but does it answer?
What?

08:20.720 --> 08:22.154
Does it answer?
Of course not.

08:22.360 --> 08:25.990
Okay. Jessica's flowers answer.
I mean, they... They talk back.

08:26.200 --> 08:27.919
You've heard them?
BURT: No, I...

08:28.120 --> 08:29.952
No, of course not. She told me.

08:30.160 --> 08:31.594
Now, you don't think that's crazy?

08:31.800 --> 08:36.477
A woman who says her flowers talk?
Jessica.

08:36.679 --> 08:41.072
It was Burt. It was Burt
who said he loved <i>The Exorcist.</i>

08:41.280 --> 08:46.435
Uh, either that
or <i>The Sound of Music.</i> Uh...
He was raving about one of them.

08:46.640 --> 08:49.872
Chester, do... Do you think
it could have been Burt?

08:50.080 --> 08:52.231
Jessica, you know
I can't stand the man.

08:52.440 --> 08:54.557
I'd be happy to pin anything on him.

08:54.760 --> 08:57.514
But I have trouble believing
he'd kill his own son.

08:57.720 --> 09:00.360
Maybe it was Danny.
Why Danny?

09:00.560 --> 09:02.552
He's so rude.

09:02.760 --> 09:04.797
Oh, I don't think
it could've been Danny.

09:05.000 --> 09:09.631
Y-you remember the time
that the trees got all infested
with those awful birds,

09:09.840 --> 09:12.036
what are their names? Uh...
Grackles.

09:12.240 --> 09:15.039
Right, the crapples.
Well... Would you...

09:15.240 --> 09:17.118
Grackles.
Right, yeah.

09:17.320 --> 09:19.312
Well, everybody wanted
to shoot the birds,

09:19.520 --> 09:22.831
and don't you remember,
Danny passed around the petition
and saved the birds.

09:23.040 --> 09:24.952
So I don't think
it could've been Danny.

09:25.160 --> 09:26.674
Maybe it was Jodie.

09:26.880 --> 09:29.076
Jodie? Please, the man
couldn't even kill himself.

09:29.280 --> 09:30.509
[LAUGHS]

09:31.040 --> 09:32.759
I think it was Chester.

09:32.960 --> 09:35.759
Come on. Chester would be afraid
of staining his clothes.

09:35.960 --> 09:37.599
Wait a minute. Wait a minute.
I think Bob's right.

09:37.800 --> 09:39.075
Yeah, sure. That's it.

09:39.280 --> 09:42.000
Chester, right? Chester did it.
Chester, that's it. Uh-huh.

09:42.200 --> 09:46.672
Maybe it was Jodie.
You know how jealous he gets. Hah.

09:46.880 --> 09:51.432
God knows, Peter was having an affair
with enough members of this family.

09:51.640 --> 09:53.791
I'm glad you said it.

09:54.480 --> 09:57.234
I think it was Corinne.
Ha. No way.

09:57.440 --> 09:58.840
What, no way? She had a motive.

09:59.040 --> 10:00.872
She was living with him.
She was jealous.

10:01.080 --> 10:02.958
Corinne did it. Corinne's the one.

10:03.160 --> 10:06.710
Well, if it wasn't any one of
the Campbells, then it was one of us.

10:06.920 --> 10:07.920
Please, Corinne.

10:08.080 --> 10:11.915
She is right. The chief of police said
that it was someone in either family,

10:12.120 --> 10:13.520
and we are all suspects.

10:13.720 --> 10:15.120
We are not.
Yes, we are.

10:15.320 --> 10:17.915
You are a suspect.
I am a suspect.

10:18.120 --> 10:21.670
So is Corinne. A-and...
And so is Eunice. So is Benson.

10:21.880 --> 10:23.155
I mean, it's amazing.

10:23.360 --> 10:27.639
Here we are, all five perfectly
nice people, enjoying breakfast...

10:27.840 --> 10:30.878
Well, actually, four because
Benson's not eating.

10:31.080 --> 10:34.073
But I mean, Chester, here we are,
five perfectly nice people,

10:34.280 --> 10:37.876
and out of these five perfectly nice
people one of us is probably a killer.

10:38.080 --> 10:42.757
I mean, a ruthless, cold-blooded,
dangerous, homicidal,
lunatic, maniac killer

10:42.960 --> 10:45.794
who, naturally, is very cleverly
disguised as a nice person.

10:46.000 --> 10:48.560
Jessica, please. Enough of this.

10:48.760 --> 10:51.480
For the last time, no one killed...

10:58.760 --> 10:59.955
It's like magic.

11:00.160 --> 11:01.958
I walk in and talking stops.

11:02.160 --> 11:04.994
Well, don't worry, I'm not staying.
I'm late for school.

11:05.200 --> 11:07.157
I'll just grab my juice
and be on my way.

11:07.360 --> 11:10.637
Dad, the last word in your sentence
was "killed."

11:12.880 --> 11:14.439
Go.

11:14.640 --> 11:17.235
Killed Peter.

11:17.440 --> 11:19.397
No one could do it.
No one would do it.

11:19.600 --> 11:22.718
Oh, I don't know.

11:22.920 --> 11:29.360
Young, good-looking, virile...

11:30.360 --> 11:32.750
That'd drive you crazy.

11:34.600 --> 11:36.000
Shut up, Benson.

11:36.200 --> 11:38.157
Well, now, Chester,
he does have a point.

11:38.360 --> 11:41.194
I mean, if we examine it,
you did have a motive.

11:41.400 --> 11:42.440
Oh, really?
JESSICA: Mm-hm.

11:42.560 --> 11:45.473
And I suppose you didn't?
Come on, Daddy. Mother?

11:45.680 --> 11:48.514
I'm not saying she did it, Corinne.
We're talking about motives here.

11:48.720 --> 11:50.473
It's ridiculous to talk about motives.

11:50.680 --> 11:53.240
I mean, if we're talking about
motives, Corinne had a motive.

11:53.440 --> 11:54.794
Oh, Eunice, please.

11:55.000 --> 11:57.754
Well, it's true. You never heard
the term, "crime of passion"?

11:57.960 --> 12:01.715
I have. Crime of passion.

12:01.920 --> 12:04.196
Oh, it's such a beautiful expression.

12:04.400 --> 12:08.076
I always wanted someone to commit
a crime of passion over me.

12:08.280 --> 12:10.875
Chester, would you have
ever killed for me?

12:13.320 --> 12:17.155
You can build a case
against anybody,
even Eunice.

12:17.360 --> 12:18.760
Oh, come on, Corinne.

12:18.960 --> 12:21.270
Well, how do we know
you weren't sleeping with him?

12:21.480 --> 12:23.119
Everybody else was.

12:24.120 --> 12:26.430
That's enough. I've had it.

12:26.640 --> 12:30.190
No one in this house
ever killed anyone.

12:30.400 --> 12:32.517
Well, I guess that eliminates
all the Tates.

12:32.720 --> 12:34.120
Yeah, which leaves us.

12:35.200 --> 12:36.600
Maybe it was Burt.

12:37.080 --> 12:39.390
I'm gonna kill him. I'm gonna kill him!

12:39.600 --> 12:41.000
I'll rip his little tongue out.

12:41.200 --> 12:44.193
Burt, what are you gonna do?
Strangle a dummy? Come on.

12:44.400 --> 12:46.915
And what am I? Your next victim?

12:47.120 --> 12:48.474
What?
BURT: Ah. You heard me.

12:48.680 --> 12:50.273
How do I know it wasn't you?
MARY: Burt.

12:50.480 --> 12:52.039
Or you.
Burt, don't say that.

12:52.240 --> 12:54.391
Sure I can, kid. You...
You're both suspects.

12:54.600 --> 12:56.159
You heard Tinkler.
Burt, come on.

12:56.360 --> 12:59.478
Heh-heh.
It could have been jealousy. Hmm.

12:59.680 --> 13:01.319
What was there to be jealous of?

13:01.520 --> 13:03.318
He was an idiot.
Oh.

13:03.520 --> 13:04.840
[SCOFFS]

13:09.880 --> 13:13.237
You're calling my dead son an idiot?

13:13.440 --> 13:14.635
Oh, I'm sorry.

13:16.040 --> 13:17.520
[SIGHS]

13:17.760 --> 13:18.910
A dead idiot.

13:19.120 --> 13:20.998
[MOUTHS WORDS]

13:21.480 --> 13:22.480
[YELLS]

13:22.640 --> 13:24.836
Dad! Dad!
Burt.

13:25.040 --> 13:26.599
[CHOKING]

13:26.840 --> 13:28.911
What are you doing?

13:29.120 --> 13:31.077
[CHOKING]

13:41.560 --> 13:42.560
[GRUNTS]

13:43.960 --> 13:45.713
[♪♪♪]

13:48.040 --> 13:49.997
[♪♪♪]

13:52.680 --> 13:55.912
So you are a supporter of the ERA?
Oh, yes.

13:56.120 --> 13:59.033
Tell me, congressman, rumour
has it that your Senate campaign

13:59.240 --> 14:02.472
is only a stepping stone on your way
to presidency. Is that true?

14:02.680 --> 14:05.400
I'm not planning that far ahead.
It's true.

14:05.600 --> 14:07.637
Waitress.

14:07.880 --> 14:10.714
Marilyn, Marilyn, don't you think
you've had enough to drink?

14:10.920 --> 14:14.994
No. Cheryl, Gretchen,
whatever your name is?

14:15.200 --> 14:17.271
Excuse me. I'll be right back.

14:17.480 --> 14:18.800
Marilyn, that's enough.

14:19.000 --> 14:23.472
Dear, I'm sorry to interrupt your
efforts to find a bed for tonight,

14:23.680 --> 14:25.876
but I'd like a martini.

14:28.200 --> 14:31.671
Marilyn, this has got to stop.
Fine.

14:31.880 --> 14:35.032
You're a congressman. Go lobby.

14:35.240 --> 14:37.709
[SNORTS THEN LAUGHS]

14:41.040 --> 14:42.679
[KNOCK ON DOOR]

14:44.080 --> 14:45.639
Oh, God.

14:46.720 --> 14:49.155
Oh, I love you.
I can't stand being without you.

14:49.360 --> 14:53.274
Oh, Walter, I don't know what to do.
Uh, move back a little.

14:53.840 --> 14:56.674
Walter, I'm afraid I'm in trouble.
Mm-hm.

14:56.880 --> 14:59.554
Oh, my God. How many weeks?

15:00.600 --> 15:03.957
No, no, no, the murder.
Peter's murder.

15:04.160 --> 15:07.710
Oh-ho-ho, that. Terrible thing.

15:07.920 --> 15:10.480
I'd like another martini, please.

15:10.680 --> 15:12.911
And this time, could you put it
in a coffee cup?

15:13.120 --> 15:14.190
Thank you.

15:15.960 --> 15:19.351
Walter? They're asking me for an alibi
and I don't have one.

15:19.560 --> 15:22.155
Are you a suspect?
Yes. Everyone is.

15:22.360 --> 15:23.840
Just tell them
where you were that night. Hmm.

15:24.040 --> 15:25.759
I was with you.

15:25.960 --> 15:29.510
In a hotel, in bed.

15:31.760 --> 15:33.160
[CLEARS THROAT]

15:33.600 --> 15:36.195
Uh... Are you really a suspect?

15:43.040 --> 15:45.635
Uh, I'll... I'll come over, uh,
about 10 tonight. Hmm?

15:45.840 --> 15:46.910
What about Marilyn?

15:47.120 --> 15:48.998
Well, it's noon,
she's on her fourth martini.

15:49.200 --> 15:51.590
By tonight at 10, she'll be in a coma.
I love you.

15:51.800 --> 15:53.598
[CHUCKLES]

15:53.800 --> 15:56.395
You leave first.
It could look funny
if we left together.

16:04.560 --> 16:06.631
What are you doing in here?

16:07.000 --> 16:10.914
Ah. Uh...
Well, darling, it's the bathroom.

16:11.120 --> 16:12.634
What does one usually do
in here?

16:12.840 --> 16:15.275
That's weird.
I was waiting for the bathroom.

16:15.480 --> 16:19.156
The door opened. Then she came
out of here, that girl reporter.

16:19.360 --> 16:20.794
You saw a woman come out
of this bathroom?

16:21.000 --> 16:24.437
Yes, that pushy little girl
who follows you around
night and day.

16:24.640 --> 16:27.280
She must really be hard up.

16:28.216 --> 16:30.096
Well, you should have come
five minutes earlier.

16:30.120 --> 16:33.272
The pilot was in here
and all the stewardesses,
and we were having a party.

16:33.480 --> 16:36.200
But I saw her, Walter.

16:36.400 --> 16:40.030
I mean, it's hard to miss her,
the girl's in heat.

16:42.120 --> 16:45.591
Marilyn, the drinking has to stop.

16:45.800 --> 16:48.280
I mean, forget about the fact
you embarrass the hell out of me.

16:48.480 --> 16:53.316
And then now you're going around
hallucinating, uh, seeing people
walk out of bathrooms.

16:53.520 --> 16:58.549
Marilyn, the... The... The drinking
has got to stop once and for all.

16:59.400 --> 17:01.357
[♪♪♪]

17:04.240 --> 17:06.914
And you should have heard
all the kids talking in school today.

17:07.119 --> 17:09.316
I am so sick of this murder.

17:09.520 --> 17:13.355
Well, you can imagine how
Peter must have felt.

17:13.560 --> 17:15.279
It's all we talk about.

17:15.480 --> 17:18.154
That's all anyone talks about.
I know.

17:18.359 --> 17:21.034
Yesterday, all the older kids
didn't even know I was alive.

17:21.240 --> 17:23.277
Today, they wouldn't leave me alone.

17:23.480 --> 17:26.314
I mean, I'm sorry Peter's dead,
but this has done a lot for me.

17:26.520 --> 17:29.479
Did you tell them that
you didn't know anything about it

17:29.680 --> 17:32.115
because the chief of police
sent you from the room?

17:32.320 --> 17:35.040
Are you joking? I made stuff up.
Billy.

17:35.240 --> 17:37.471
All the help on the block
started a pool.

17:37.680 --> 17:42.197
Good. In the summer,
the troops can go swimming.

17:48.240 --> 17:49.720
They're all taking bets.

17:49.920 --> 17:54.199
You've got more money on you
than Ali in the last fight.

17:54.480 --> 17:56.153
[DOORBELL RINGS]

17:59.600 --> 18:02.115
You want me to get that?

18:07.280 --> 18:08.600
Would you mind?

18:13.680 --> 18:17.230
Well, now I know how Elizabeth Taylor
and Jackie Onassis feel,

18:17.440 --> 18:20.478
walking down the street,
with all that staring and whispering.

18:20.680 --> 18:23.149
I don't know how they ever
get anything accomplished.

18:23.360 --> 18:26.592
Of course, it is worse
for them because everybody
wants their autograph.

18:26.800 --> 18:28.678
So far, nobody's asked me for mine.

18:28.880 --> 18:32.794
But if they do,
I've decided to keep it really
quite simple, just something like:

18:33.000 --> 18:35.276
"Best wishes, Jessica Tate."

18:37.760 --> 18:39.831
Sherlock Holmes.

18:41.880 --> 18:43.997
Uh... Evening. I'm sorry
to interrupt your dinner,

18:44.200 --> 18:47.193
but I have, ahem, an important
announcement to make.

18:47.480 --> 18:50.439
Ooh. Is that prime ribs?
Yes.

18:50.640 --> 18:53.314
My favourite thing in this world
is prime ribs, but,

18:53.520 --> 18:55.159
oh, gosh, I haven't had that since,

18:55.360 --> 18:58.398
oh, well, it must be going on
15 years now. Ha-ha.

18:58.600 --> 19:00.273
Tinkler, what's your announcement?

19:00.480 --> 19:04.076
You haven't had prime ribs
for 15 years?

19:04.280 --> 19:06.200
Uh, you know how it is,
the little woman... Uh...

19:06.240 --> 19:09.074
That's, uh... That's my wife.
Yeah, yeah, yeah.

19:09.880 --> 19:12.031
She says she hates to cook it
for just the two of us.

19:12.240 --> 19:13.469
There's too much leftovers.

19:13.680 --> 19:15.034
Tinkler? Come on.
Yeah. Oh, yeah? What, huh?

19:15.240 --> 19:17.550
Well, you could make sandwiches.

19:17.760 --> 19:19.319
Now, that's what I told my wife,

19:19.520 --> 19:22.513
but she said we'd have to go
on having sandwiches for months.

19:22.720 --> 19:25.633
Well, if worse came to worst,
you could give some to your dogs.

19:25.840 --> 19:27.160
Uh... No dogs.
JESSICA: Oh...

19:27.360 --> 19:31.274
Tinkler, uh, could you make
this announcement of yours, please?

19:31.480 --> 19:34.791
My wife's allergic. We've got birds,
though. Two parakeets.

19:35.000 --> 19:36.000
[IMITATES WINGS FLAPPING]

19:36.160 --> 19:38.197
Through the house.

19:38.400 --> 19:41.677
I don't know if birds eat roast beef.
TINKLER: I don't think so.

19:41.880 --> 19:43.872
Tinkler, what do you want?

19:44.080 --> 19:46.834
I wouldn't mind a taste
of that roast beef.

19:47.040 --> 19:49.714
Yes, of course. Sit down
in Eunice's place. She's not here.

19:49.920 --> 19:52.879
I know. Eunice is in, uh, Washington.
Hmm.

19:53.080 --> 19:55.120
Yeah, but then, uh...
But she's no longer a suspect.

19:55.240 --> 19:56.959
Oh, Chester, isn't that wonderful?

19:57.160 --> 20:00.153
Benson, please get the chief of police
a plate of roast beef.

20:00.360 --> 20:01.999
Heh-heh-heh.
Nope.

20:04.400 --> 20:06.119
Well, I eliminated you, too.

20:06.320 --> 20:08.960
Rare, medium or well-done?

20:10.440 --> 20:11.715
Rare, please.

20:11.920 --> 20:14.310
Tinkler, you came
to make an announcement.

20:14.520 --> 20:16.159
What is it?
Ahem. Oh, yeah, right. Uh...

20:16.360 --> 20:20.832
I, uh... I've come to make an
announcement about the, uh...
The investigation.

20:21.040 --> 20:24.112
Mm-hm.
Uh... Oh, that looks good, yeah.

20:24.320 --> 20:27.074
You came to make an announcement.
Right.

20:27.280 --> 20:28.396
[CHUCKLES]

20:28.600 --> 20:31.798
Oh. Is that... Is that what I think it is?
Huh? Huh?

20:32.000 --> 20:34.196
Horseradish sauce.

20:34.400 --> 20:35.959
Boy, do I love horseradish sauce.

20:36.160 --> 20:37.310
[CHUCKLES]

20:37.520 --> 20:40.831
Tinkler, are you going to tell us
or are you gonna move in?

20:41.040 --> 20:42.759
Oh, yeah.

20:42.960 --> 20:46.192
Right, well, uh, ahem, we've, uh...
We've narrowed down the leads,

20:46.400 --> 20:49.837
and, uh, we've made some
conclusions, and, uh...

20:50.040 --> 20:52.077
Would you pass the salt, please?

20:52.280 --> 20:54.511
Your conclusions, Tinkler.

20:54.720 --> 20:57.189
Oh, it's wonderful.
Marvellous, wonderful. Mm-hm.

20:57.400 --> 20:58.629
Thank you.

20:58.840 --> 21:01.480
Yes, we've, uh...
We've eliminated Benson.

21:01.680 --> 21:06.152
We've eliminated Eunice
and we've eliminated, uh...

21:07.000 --> 21:09.754
Oh, my. Heh-heh.

21:10.280 --> 21:12.556
Is... Is that sweet-potato pudding?

21:12.760 --> 21:14.080
That's right. Ha-ha-ha.

21:14.280 --> 21:15.634
[LAUGHS] Oh, my God.

21:15.840 --> 21:18.674
My grandmother used to make that.
JESSICA: Oh.

21:18.880 --> 21:22.396
Go on, Tinkler.
Don't mind if I do.

21:23.320 --> 21:27.234
Oh. Would you please tell us
why you came here?

21:27.440 --> 21:30.160
Uh... But the, uh...
Uh, the youngster,
uh... Hmm? Hmm?

21:30.360 --> 21:33.239
Uh, Billy?
TINKLER: Ahem.

21:33.480 --> 21:35.233
Okay, fine. I'm leaving.

21:35.440 --> 21:37.909
It's a wonder that I ever learned
the English language.

21:38.120 --> 21:40.112
I'll be in my room
playing with my CB.

21:40.320 --> 21:43.438
Maybe somewhere, somebody in
this world would like to talk to me.

21:44.360 --> 21:45.635
Continue, Tinkler.

21:45.840 --> 21:47.559
Mm? Oh, yes, well, as I was saying,

21:47.760 --> 21:50.280
we've eliminated Benson
and we've, uh...
We've eliminated Eunice.

21:50.440 --> 21:53.990
Uh, Tinkler, are you saying
that it's one of the Campbells?

21:54.200 --> 21:57.716
Oh. No, no, no, the murderer
is still in this house.

21:57.920 --> 22:00.560
Hah! Who is it?
Well, it's...

22:00.760 --> 22:03.116
[COUGHING, CHOKING]

22:03.360 --> 22:06.876
Well, who is it, you idiot?

22:07.080 --> 22:09.470
I think he means we're getting closer.

22:12.880 --> 22:16.999
Water, water.
Walter. He said it's Walter, Chester.

22:17.200 --> 22:19.635
There's no Walter in this house.

22:19.840 --> 22:21.957
Water.
No, no. Water.

22:22.160 --> 22:23.719
Water. He says it's water.

22:25.160 --> 22:27.072
Who's water, for God's sake?

22:28.800 --> 22:32.316
It must be a clue. Uh... Uh...

22:32.560 --> 22:33.560
Lives near water?

22:34.040 --> 22:35.040
[MOUTHS WORD]

22:35.240 --> 22:36.959
Sounds like water?

22:38.280 --> 22:39.509
Oh, I've got it.
JESSICA: What?

22:39.720 --> 22:42.155
He needs water to drink, right?

22:42.360 --> 22:45.671
Yeah, i-it...
It's a person who drinks water.

22:45.880 --> 22:49.510
It's a person who, uh,
doesn't drink water?

22:49.720 --> 22:52.110
No, it's Corinne.

22:52.320 --> 22:53.515
Corinne?

22:53.720 --> 22:57.760
Corinne Tate, you're under arrest
for the murder of Peter Campbell.

22:58.640 --> 23:00.040
Ma?

23:00.240 --> 23:01.356
[♪♪♪]

23:08.200 --> 23:09.200
[♪♪♪]

23:09.360 --> 23:12.194
ANNOUNCER:
<i>Will Chester and Jessica really</i>
<i>stop fooling around with other people</i>

23:12.400 --> 23:15.040
<i>and actually start fooling around</i>
<i>with each other?</i>

23:15.240 --> 23:17.197
<i>Will Mrs. McCallam</i>
<i>find out her husband</i>

23:17.400 --> 23:19.915
<i>is giving more than just an interview</i>
<i>to Eunice?</i>

23:20.120 --> 23:23.238
<i>Will the airlines increase</i>
<i>the size of their bathrooms</i>

23:23.440 --> 23:25.477
<i>to accommodate larger parties?</i>

23:25.680 --> 23:29.833
<i>Will Corinne be jailed,</i>
<i>tried, and convicted</i>
<i>for the murder of Peter?</i>

23:30.040 --> 23:34.478
<i>Will the Tates ever invite Chief Tinkler</i>
<i>to a roast-beef dinner again?</i>

23:34.680 --> 23:36.399
<i>These questions, and many others,</i>

23:36.600 --> 23:40.640
<i>will be answered on</i>
<i>next week's episode of</i> Soap.

23:47.520 --> 23:49.477
